    <div class="details-content">
        <div class="admonition-content">This article explores the Café Wall Illusion, where parallel lines appear curved or slanted due to alternating black and white squares and horizontal offsets. Built using LaTeX TikZ, the article provides a complete explanation of both the code and the perceptual mechanisms behind it.&quot;</div></div></div>
<h2 id="introduction" class="headerLink">
    <a href="#introduction" class="header-mark"></a>25 Introduction</h2><p>Have you ever looked at a tiled wall or brick pattern that seemed wavy even though the lines were perfectly straight?<br>
This is known as the <strong>Café Wall Illusion</strong>, an optical illusion where <strong>parallel horizontal lines</strong> appear tilted or curved due to the <strong>alternating contrast of black and white tiles</strong> and <strong>horizontal offset between rows</strong>.</p>]]></description>
