    <div class="details-content">
        <div class="admonition-content">This article discusses the circle illusion, where two identical central circles appear different in size due to surrounding visual context. Built with LaTeX TikZ, this article provides a complete explanation of the code structure and perceptual science behind it.</div></div></div>
<h2 id="introduction" class="headerLink">
    <a href="#introduction" class="header-mark"></a>28 Introduction</h2><p>In the realm of visual perception, the human brain often processes size <strong>relatively</strong> rather than <strong>absolutely</strong>.<br>
One of the most well-known examples of this is the <strong>Ebbinghaus Illusion</strong>, or <strong>Circle Illusion</strong>, in which two identical circles appear to be of different sizes due to the surrounding shapes.</p>]]></description>
